# Introduction
Multiple recent experimental results have shown a significant size-effect in mechanical properties when the dimensions of the specimen or the probed material volume become small. The classical continuum theories, on the other hand, lack the capability of representing such effects since they do not include any internal length scale. Consequently, these theories are expected to fail when the specimen size or the wavelength of the perturbation become comparable with the internal length scale(s) of the material.

Several modifications of the classical elasticity formulation have been proposed to address this deficiency. They are of integral non-local or gradient type and, as a common feature, include one or several intrinsic length scales. Their predictions reduce to those of local continuum theories when the specimen size is much larger than the internal length scale. (Eringen and Edelen, 1972; Kunin, 1982; Valanis, 2000, Altan and Aifantis, 1992; Gutkin and Aifantis, 1999).

In the integral formulation of non-local elasticity due to Eringen (1972) the constitutive equation is expressed in terms of a non-local kernel introduced to account for the effect of long-range interatomic forces. The stress at point x is a function of the strain at all points y in the body, through a weighting kernel . Specifically, one writes

`\[\sigma_{ij}\left(x\right)=\int_V{\alpha\left(|x-y|\right)t_{ij}(y)dV(y)}\]`

where `\(t_{ij}(y)\)` are the usual local stresses at point y. Hence, `\(\alpha\)` weighs the elastic constants of the material. The kernel is often assumed to be Gaussian

`\[\alpha\left(|x-y|\right) = \alpha_0 e^{-\left(\frac{|x-y|}{mb}\right)^2} \]`

where `\(mb\)` is an intrinsic length scale (in units of the lattice parameter `\(b\)`), and `\(\alpha_0\)` is found from the normalization condition for `\(\alpha\)`, `\(\int_V{\alpha\left(|x-y|\right)}dV(y) = 1 \)`, to be `\(\alpha_0 = \frac{1}{\pi \sqrt(\pi)}\)` `\(m^3\)`.

The selection of the internal length scale `\(mb\)` is still a controversial issue. This metric provides the order of magnitude of the threshold below which the non-local theory departs from the predictions of the corresponding local formulation.

The common feature of all non-local formulations is the elimination of stress field singularities. The gradient elasticity solution shows no singularity in both stress and strain fields at the core of dislocations. Furthermore, the strain energy is finite at sites where local elasticity predicts stress singularities and infinite strain energy density.

# A new non-local elasticity kernel
The non-local formulation of elasticity has been introduced as a correction to the local theory in order to account for the long-ranged interatomic forces. The shape of the non-local kernel is assumed therefore to represent the actual atomic-scale interactions. However, the Gaussian kernel of eqn. (1) is incompatible with even a simple pair potential of the Lennard-Jones type. The first argument in this sense is related to the short range of the kernel. Even with the largest non-locality parameter suggested in the literature (m = 0.5), the kernel is so short ranged that a displacement of a first neighbor located at distance b from the representative atom, effectively has no influence on the central atom. Hence, the actual interatomic interactions are not directly represented.

The second argument is rooted in the following observation. In a lattice in which interactions are described by a pair potential similar to the Lennard-Jones, a shift of a neighboring atom located at a distance smaller than the inflection point of the potential, away from the central atom, produces on the reference atom a force in the direction of the shift. A similar relative displacement of a neighbor located farther than the inflection point, leads to a force on the representative atom in the direction opposite to that of the shift. This suggests that the kernel should change sign at a distance corresponding to the inflection point of the interatomic potential.

These considerations motivate the use of a modified kernel in the continuum theory. The functional form of the new kernel is

`\[\alpha\left(|x-y|\right) = \alpha_0\left(1-n\left(\frac{|x-y|}{b}\right)^2\right) e^{\left(\frac{|x-y|}{mb}\right)^2}\]`

where n is a second non-dimensional non-locality parameter. The parameter m controls the range of the kernel, while n sets the distance from the representative atom at which the kernel changes sign. While with a Gaussian kernel of the form (1) m is limited to 0.5, the kernel (3) allows much larger values of m which, in turn, means longer range. Figure 1 shows qualitatively the kernel (3) along with its Gaussian equivalent (at same m).

A normalization relationship similar to that used for the kernel in eqn. (1) holds, and the parameter `\(\alpha_0\)` becomes `\(\alpha_0 = \frac{1}{\pi\sqrt{\pi}\left(m^3 - 1.5nm^5\right)}\)`.

