The results obtained with the fully non-local model, in which both the continuum and the cohesive law are rendered non-local do not differ significantly from those obtained in the case in which the cohesive law is kept local (Figures 3 and 4).

It has been observed that the functional form of the rebound force (local or non-local) describing the interactions across the glide plane has a major effect on the predicted core shape and Peierls stress.

# Non-local rubber elasticity
A non-local formulation of rubber elasticity with applications to nanostructured materials is developed. In general, stress has an entropic and an energetic component. The energetic component is due to short range interactions of the representative atom with its neighbors, while the entropic component is due to chain conformation changes upon deformation. In rubbers, the entropic component is dominant. Both components are intrinsically non-local; stress at a point depends on the deformation in a whole neighborhood of that point. The range of non-locality of the entropic component is on the order of the chain size (or distance between cross-links), and is much larger than the range of non-locality of the energetic component. Non-locality becomes important when the deformation field varies significantly over a distance comparable with the internal length scale of the material (large gradients). Here, non-local formulations are derived for both the energetic and the entropic components of stress for a system of polymeric chains.

For small deformations, linear non-local elasticity may be used for the energetic component of stress and a kernel may be derived within the integral formalism of non-local elasticity. This kernel is derived based on the atomic scale structure found from atomistic simulations. Since small deformations elasticity is controlled by localized energetic interactions (bonded and non-bonded), chain conformations are unimportant. The kernel is similar to the modified kernel in Fig. 1.

The situation is more complicated for the entropic component of stress (the dominant component in rubbers and polymers above the glass transition). First, in the classical theory of rubber elasticity, the stress is defined as an average over a volume comparable to the volume occupied by a chain, i.e. it is assume that the chain is subjected to a homogeneous deformation. Second, the material response is highly non-linear, the non-linearity being of both constitutive (e.g. Langevin chains) and geometric (chain convection) nature. To mitigate the first constraint, the classical rubber elasticity theory was reformulated such to associate a stress tensor to a much smaller volume of material, a volume comparable in size to a "bead" of the atomistic model. This is the same volume with which one associates the energetic component of stress. This led to an analytic formulation of stress as an integral over a spherical volume surrounding the current point with radius equal to the chain radius of gyration. Due to the intrinsic non-linearity of the response, a kernel could not be separated.

The details of this work were published in a special issue of the Journal of Multiscale Computational Engineering dedicated to linking discrete and continuum models {% cite picu_nonlocal_2003 %}

